,Recommended,221640,8268865,"Posted: 24 December, 2013",all,DoctorSchwartz,"Probably the most addicting game I have played in my entire life. Its complexity of maneuvering around the hexagons combined with the trippiness of the maps, makes this one hell of an experience. The difficulty of the game is quite high, so play this game with a mindset that you ARE NOT in fact the master. However, when you crash and burn in the game, it never becomes a rageful experience. You immediately are pulled into the draw of playing just one more round. The rounds are short enough that you don't feel as though you wasted time when you die.This game is almost a replacement for drugs. While Audiosurf is like smoking weed, Super Hexagon is like being on straight acid.  It fits under Level 3 of the Psychedelic Experience ranking:Level 3Very obvious visuals, everything looks curved and warped, patterns and kaleidoscopes seen on walls and faces. Some mild hallucinations such as rivers flowing in wood grain or 'mother of pearl' surfaces. Closed-eye hallucinations become 3-dimensional. There is some confusing of the senses (synesthesia). Time distortions and 'moments of eternity'. Movement at times becomes extremely difficult (too much effort required). Can be achieved with common doses of LSD, psilocybin mushrooms, peyote, ayahuasca, and Super Hexagon.Welcome to Super Hexagon, the cheapest, but most addicting game you will find in your lifetime.10/10"
