76561197998117014,Recommended,221640,10281974,"Posted: 29 May, 2014",all,Mister Ether,"This game is self-improvement that feels like self-abuse, but when you make progress you know you've earned it.Super Hexagon is entirely a skill game.  Besides the obvious hand-eye-coordination, Super Hexagon heavily affects your ability to focus on several levels.  It hits your brain's ability to track/manipulate a small, moving object, all while subjected to visual distraction and spacial distortion that prevent you from mentally caching information.  It requires you to mentally buffer between 3 and 6 units of movement, with one move falling off the buffer as you perform it and a new move being added to the end at the same time.  It also taps into the brain's ability to slow perception.You have to personally improve in order to proceed.  The most luck will do is buy you an extra couple units of time before you die and start over.  There is no grinding or level memorization (though there is lightpatternrecognition).  You cannot beat this game without being good at it.  Since it is a skill game, though, the abilities you develop to focus and make buffered, rapid decisions will carry over to anything else you do that call for the same things.I think that's what's so addictive about Super Hexagon.  The knowledge thatit's making you better at somethingwhile the mental stress and flashing colors are eroding your sanity.  The thing that keeps it from being too frustrating isit is alwaysyour faultwhen you die.When you stop making mistakes you stop dying.Here are some things you should know about the game play:*  Epileptics shouldn't even watch the video, let alone play the game.*  This is basically a randomly-generated maze, except the walls are constantly hurtling towards you, every aspect of the game is designed to cause you to lose track of what you're doing, and death is instant the first time you make an error.  You can't pause or make the walls stop coming.  You just keep navigating your way forever or until you die.* Everything occurs in what I'll call ""units"", which will represent 1/6 the amount of time for what's just beyond the edge of the screen to reach the middle.  Each wall is between 1 and 2 units of time in depth (yes, I'm using time as a measurement of depth and yes that makes sense).*  In playing this game you will maintain a mental buffer of what you'll be doing over 6 units of time.  This is a live action game, so I mean you'll literally be doing this in your head.  Most of the things thrown at you will come in blocks where you have 2 units of time to move (or stay still).*  As you're executing the current move and removing it from your mental buffer you're also adding 1 - 2 units to the opposite end of the buffer.  Reminder: this buffer exists solely in your own mind.*  You can do three things in this game: rotate clockwise, rotate counterclockwise, and stay still.  Doing the wrong one usually kills you.Regarding some complaints I've heard on the controls:*  I've heard people recommend using a controller.  I don't think that advice is universal.  I found it easier to use the A and D keys from playing a lot of games where you use your left hand and the WASD keys even though I am right-handed.*  Your control of the triangle/cursor is inexact.  It's important to reverse direction (when possible) to recenter it.  The reason for movement being freeform is because you will occasionally need to move a hair's width over the line to dodge one wall then immediately reverse direction to avoid being killed by the next wall.  If your movement was less twitchy you could not do this.*  There is a very slight delay between pressing one of the two move buttons and your cursor moving.  If you hold a button down you will move in that direction (""spin"") until you release it.  This is faster than tapping to move the same amount of distance because it only has one delay, but requires better timing to avoid killing yourself.  This is not accidental; there will be times when doing anything other than a controlled spin will be too slow (which will kill you)....Despite how that might sound, this game is actually a lot of fun because it challenges your brain.  This is purely a game.  Super Hexagon makes no attempt to be art nor is it a medium for art.  It is a work of craft."
