,Recommended,221640,9323262,"Posted: 2 March, 2014",all,Charter,"Super Hexagon can be a lesson to people who believe they can never do something. If you take the game and its ""Easy"" difficult, which is aptly named 'hard' It may seem difficult but if you keep trying and building up your memory and reaction time, you can achieve it easily. After you play for as long as I did the patterns start to merge together and you subconciously know what is going to happen, you predict the random generation.As you feel your way through the first three levels you start to learn that the game has a few tricks that you won't expect your first hour or three, but as the advisor speaks its single words to you ""Line"" ""Triangle"" Square"" ""Pentagon"" ""Hexagon"" you feel empowered after each of these dauntful yet encouraging quotes. And once you begin to get higher scores like mine on the 'Hard' difficulty of 5+ minutes, everytime you reach a new minute you here ""Awesome"" like you have finally accomplished a goal and milestone. But as the adventure continues to the final levels, you start to feel a shadow looking down on you as you reach an impassable barrier on your quest to 60 seconds.With every minute passing you feel more and more frustrated by the lack of progress until you finally feel your way through the patterns that you haven't yet seen, you being to make the progress you wanted and are on top of the world, then at 50+ seconds the game pulls a trick and you are back to zero. The cycle of time starts again and you are stuck there. And once you beat the game the milestones only continue to grow, forever and eventually into 5, 10, 15 minutes of Hexagon.This is the Super Hexagon way, a challenge and a frustration, but also a accomplishing task. The six-sided figure will always bring light in a rough day if you are determined to take the time to sate its thirst for a challenger."
