,Recommended,221640,9024695,"Posted: 8 February, 2014",all,MrHH,"Most games have a learning curve, which this doesn't have, but it does have an attitude curve. You will most likely think this game is dumb at first. You will push this game away to a backburner, but not for long. Eventually, something deep inside will cause you to give this game another go. And from that go, many more will occur.The controls (using left/right arrow keys) are accurate and precise once you spend a bit of time on them.The music, while simple, motivates you to keep going in a stage. If you die a lot though, it can become repetitive, but it's not that bad.Visually, the game varies by stage. Some stages have very little contrast between the colors, but you will get used to it.Overall, this game will keep you coming back for more until there is nothing more to do. Unlike simliar games, you will not get mad when you lose, except when you first get it. Battling with yourself is what this game will evoke, but there is also leaderboards if you need an external motive to push you. Once you get into Super Hexagon, you will never be able to get out."
