,Recommended,221640,8265195,"Posted: 24 December, 2013",all,Bafooba (soontobeback),"going to rewrite this review with sort of a ""first impressions but not"" prespective to get rid of that terrible old review of mine.I have saved the previous review to pastebin for historical purposes.I'm going to censor my swearing just so I don't have a collection of hearts adorning this review.So what do I have to say in rewritting this review?Well to start off, let me spill the beans, I honestly secretly hated this game but others liked it and the music was f**king stellar so I ""recommended"" it.Why did I hate this game? Because holy sh*t, its controlls seemed utterly busted.Spoilers, they aren't really.This game has a slight amount of lag due to vsync which will affect your play, it will make the controlls seem pretty sloppy and sluggish, that was the reason for the ""this game feels like your spinning around with a sack of potatoes"" comment in my old review (bad grammar intact), I just didn't know it.So does turning vsync off help?Maybe it's confirmation bias but I was immediately able to destroy my old score on the Hexagon stage when it was turned off, so I'd say there's no harm in it.Well I WOULD say there's no harm in it but...ᵗʰᵃᵗ'ᵈ ᵇᵉ ᶫʸᶦᶰᵍ⋅You see, if you're not familiar with what Vsync is, it's a term that stands for Vertical Synchronization, it prevents what is known as tearingwhich looks like this.In my experience, having vsync off in most games is fine but in Super Hexagon this is not the case, in fact Super Hexagon has some of the worst screen tearing I've seen in a video game and this tearing can be quite distracting, I'm not sure if this varies from monitor to monitor but at least in my case I'm pitted with two options: Keep Vsync on and prevent screen tearing and never complete a single stage or turn it off, bite the bullet, and play the game. Thankfully I'm able to eventually ignore what I consider god awful tearing but your experience may vary.What else do I have to say about the game?Well now that I can actually play it and failure feels like my own fault, it's pretty good.The game has a pseudo rhythm game vibe that I can appreciate and the challenge it presents is fun to overcome.I would have more to say but I've only completed the Hexagon stage, I will update this review when I have more knowledge on the game.https://pastebin.com/EucmeE7n"
,Recommended,221640,8700530,"Posted: 13 January, 2014",all,spondy,"Upon first starting this game, you'll realize that there are no ""Easy"" or ""Medium"" difficulty settings. Keeping this in mind, you nervously select the first mode you see: ""Hexagon,"" or ""Hard"" difficulty. You'll immediately not be able to breathe or blink as your tiny triangle first appears on the screen, mostly likely dying within a few seconds, obliterated against a flashing, rotating wall. Try as you might, you just can't seem to get past the first few seconds of the game. Occasionally you might get lucky and add a few more seconds onto your personal best. All the while, the only thing on your mind is dodging the shapes; nothing else in the world is more engrossing and entrancing when this game sucks you in with its trippy yet simple graphics and absolutely killer 8-bit soundtrack. Eventually you get frustrated enough to quit the game; that annoying female voice reminds you of your defeat with a dismissive ""GAME. OVER."" every time you mess up, and it's been getting on your nerves. This is the point where some people never come back to this game. However, if you're like me, you come back the next day to try again. This game, while very daunting at first, becomes much more doable with practice. Through the countless times you hear that annoying disembodied voice proclaim your demise, the feeling of achieving a new high score is something truly incredible."
