,Recommended,221640,11168450,"Posted: 10 July, 2014",all,INGMO,"This game was my life for several months.During my reflex test, I kicked my doctor in the jaw.10/10 would be restrained again.Kidding.However, I am not jesting about the 10/10. Or being restrained.Super Hexagon is a simple game about a small triangle revolving around a center hexagon, dodging shards seemingly made of other hexagons. You are the triangle. You cannot touch the shards.As opposed to the original Flash version (which had one level and two colors), Super Hexagon contains six levels, each requiring you to stay alive for one eternity-- er, minute. Oh, and there's more colors.The game is unrelentingly difficult, but oh-so-addicting. The game plays with only two buttons during gameplay, and has several ways of doing so (arrow keys, mouse buttons, gamepad triggers). The game's visuals are psychedelic, color changing and, in the first two levels, seemingly on an axis. You better be darn sure that you're not epileptic or have motion sickness. However, for a person with neither (yours truly), the effect was mesmerizing.The six levels consist of three different levels (Hexagon, Hexagoner, Hexagonest), and then three ""Hyper Mode"" versions, which are faster and with different patterns. Trust me, you WILL work to complete every world.Despite the theoretical six minutes of gameplay that this game would (theoretically) provide, hours will be poured into trying to complete every level... and then some to break your own (or someone else's) high score. Heck, it took me 17 hours to beat a $4 game, and, I tell you, I feel like I need to be locked up on robbery charges at that price.6 levels, 6 sides, 60 seconds. Yep.Also, I legitimately cried at the end. That's actually true.I have never said that a game is perfect before. Even my favorite games that I hold in such high respect still have several flaws which I acknowledge. However, due to the concentrated nature of Super Hexagon's gameplay, it is impossible to find any faults within it. Really.At this point, it sounds like I'm simply ecstatic about the game, and will shout praises and begin handing out brochures about the dangers of other games. The truth it, I feel that everything I wrote here is true. Every last word.Except the beginning joke.Seriously, 10/10 ""would buy again""And yes.  I actually would."
