,Not Recommended,221640,12193305,"Posted: 22 September, 2014",all,Fargin Noob,"Overall, I have three complaints about the game: 1) the collision detection on your cursor is imprecise, leading to situations where you die when you're ""on"" the line, even though you're to the correct side; 2) the randomness of everything means that you're not really getting better as much as you are hoping for a randomly generated pattern that is easy to navigate; and 3) the controls are not really as good as they should be for the twitchiness of the game.On point number three, specifically using left or right to move isn't fast enough if you go the wrong way. You have the option, for instance, to go left or right around a hexagonal block to reach the open space, but that is a false choice because the speed of the collision blocks vs the speed of the cursor is such that you can only make it the shortest distance. That's a problem. Further, there's a vast imprecision about where your cursor ends leading quite often to problem number 1. Had there been some lead up to the difficulty the game starts at to give you a good feel for the cursor speed, that might be one thing, but there's not.I have a hard time recommending the game. Its gameplay is shallow, and the controls aren't tight enough to allow for the difficulty curve it's asking for. The two best things going for the game are the quick replayability (no loading screens, etc.), and the excellent chiptune soundtrack.One final note: there are no cards for the game, and that's severely disappointing considering how simple the game is."
