,Recommended,221640,8597633,"Posted: 6 January, 2014",all,MetaWaddleDoo,"It's very rare to see a game as simple as Super Hexagon feel like such a fresh experience.  I can't remember the last time I've enjoyed a game this much, either.  Most of my time spent playing games is just used to forget about the sorrow of my sad, pathetic excuse for an existence.  But when I turned on Super Hexagon, some light bulb turned on inside of me.  One that had been turned off since I was a little child.  I was having so much fun playing this game.  I couldn't put it down, and I couldn't stop thinking about it when I wasn't home.In the game, you control a little cursor that moves around a hexagon.  Press right to move clockwise, and left to move counter-clockwise.  That's all there is to the controls.  The purpose of the game is to dodge incoming lines moving towards the hexagon and to stay alive as long as possible.  There's 3 different levels at first, appropriately labeled as 'Hard', 'Harder', and 'Hardest'.  You can unlock 'Hyper' versions of these levels after reaching the 60 second mark in a stage.At a first glance, the game seems like it'll be relatively easy.  And then you die right away.  And then you say to yourself ""Crap... I can do better than that.""  And then you die again.  You repeat this process for about an hour, and realize that you still haven't gotten further than 10 seconds.  You curse the gods and the heavens, go pace around for a bit, and then come back and repeat the process all over again for another hour.  And then somehow you've reached 60 seconds and feel like you have the reflexes of a god.  And even after beating all of the levels, I still can't put this game down.  The game is just so much fun at it's core that I keep playing to try and get better times on each stage.I should also mention that the music in this game is incredible.  There's only 3 tracks, one for each stage, but they're implemented in a way that helps keep them from being too repetitive.  Whenever you restart a level, the game starts the track from one of three different spots, somewhat giving the player the illusion of progression.  And each song seems to have one melody that only pops up when you're 30 seconds to 60 seconds into a level.  This helps build up tension your first time through, as the music becomes unfamiliar right as you're getting close to beating the level.If you're the kind of gamer who feels like a game should have a lot of content and things to see, then avoid this game.  You can see 50% of what this game has to offer in approximately 30 seconds.  If you have a little bit of imagination, then pretend the 3 stages you played spin faster and have different background colors.  You've now seen 100% of what the game has to offer, all within less than a minute.  But, if you're a gamer who feels like a game isn't finished until you've completely mastered it, then prepare for hours and hours of fun with Super Hexagon.  This is a game in it's purest form.  No fluff.  No story.  No handholding.  Just... a ♥♥♥♥ing game.  Something that is now exceedingly rare."
