76561198083928999,Recommended,221640,20204152,"Posted: 1 January, 2016",all,The Judas Goat,"Super Hexagon is the world's leading hexagon simulator. Use of it can and will train you thouroughly in several skills that are so completely inapplicable to real life that whence you enter the game, you won't have them at all.This game is for you is you are willing to work for it - the level of fun isn't quite Dwarf Fortress, but boy golly is it ever *not* casual. The gameplay is sparse, and uncomplicated. The controls are simple, and highly responsive. But each jump in difficulty is definitely a *jump*: if you completed the last level, you will still die quite a bit on the next one.Subjectively, each additional level feels about 1.5x harder than the last; with major difficulties being the first three levels, and the last level. The fourth and fifth levels are just faster variations of levels one and two with a unique piece (pattern to dodge) thrown in. The sixth level is aalso like this, but is *so* much faster that the difficulty spike is markedly harder.To put this in perspective, at the time of writing this review, I've broken into the top 5000 players on Level 4, I'm in the top 8000 for level five, and I *still* have not even beaten level six (beating a level is survivng for 60 seconds).So... yep. Definitely a bit harder than the other two.Beyond gameplay, the only other thing that bears comment is the soundtrack. In two words: exquisite chiptunes. The artist responsible for this music, Chipzel, composes the music on the sound chips of Nintendo Gameboys - the handhelds that came out in 1989, not the later ones - and then augments it in a more modern environment. A pleasure to listen to if you like that kind of thing. If not, there are several guides written by members of the community on how to change or disable the music.Overall, 11/10 permutohedrons are awesome. You will hate this game if you can't take failure; you will love it if you love having to fight for every iota of success."
