76561198139006148,Recommended,221640,16695964,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,Dr. Ambiguous,"Quick Breakdown:An arcade style game where you play as a triangle trying to survive deadly lines while pulsating electronic music plays. It’s like having a seizure while tripping balls on heavy psychedelic drugs.Length:3+Score:6/10Full Review:Super Hexagonis a pretty simple and straightforward game. Now admittedly, when I first saw screenshots for the game, and even the first time I watched a video on it, I really had no idea what the hell was going on. This was a combination of the trippy visuals, and just how simplistic it is graphically.You play as a triangle, which circles around a hexagon at the center of the screen. You simply use the arrow keys to move clockwise and counter-clockwise. As you circle around the center, lines will move from the outside of the screen towards the center hexagon. If the lines hit you, you “die.”The game has 6 levels, 3 you begin with, and 3 that are hard modes of the levels that you unlock for completing the corresponding basic level. To “complete” a level you must survive for 60 seconds. I put complete in quotes in that last sentence, because levels last until you die, there’s no set end point. However, the game rewards you with an achievement for lasting 60 seconds and considers it as beating the level.Levels are comprised of different patterns of lines that you must dodge, for each 10 seconds that you survive, you unlock an additional set of patterns (up to the first 60 seconds). On some levels the center hexagon even morphs into a pentagon or a square to shake things up a bit. Other than that, there’s not a whole lot else to the gameplay.The music in the game consists of 3 different electronic songs, and they fit the game pretty well, correctly matching the trippy visuals, with rapidly changing colours. I just wish there were than only 3 tracks in the game, as while the tracks are good, it’d be nice to have a few more.The gameplay itself is pretty damn difficult, much more than one would likely expect from such a simple game. As such, I’ve not been able to beat the game, and I’ve so far only managed to last the full minute on only the first two levels. I’m not sure that I’ll be able to complete any other levels, though I’ll likely play it a bit more here and there. Chances are though, that even if you can’t beat the game (quite likely), you’ll probably be able to get at least 3 hours of entertainment out of it before you move on to another game. Given that the game is only $3 normally, and sometimes goes on sale for $1, I think that’s a reasonable price to pay for what you get.Super Hexagonisn’t a must have game, but it’s still a fun little time killer now and then. Chances are you won’t beat it, but it’s more of an arcade game where you see how long you can last anyway. Give it a chance if that’s your sort of thing."
