,Recommended,221640,17179659,"Posted: 22 July, 2015",all,SabreCat,"Years ago, I read an essay aboutGeometry Warsthat praised it as a ""video game"" of the purest possible sort: no narrative, no simulation, an experience not expressible in any other medium than the digital arcade. That essay stuck with me, and it comes to mind whenever I play a minimalist arcade game. Super Hexagon falls into that rarefied genre.Super Hexagonis a neuron trainer, an activity of mental self-construction on a basal level. You can't think your way to victory; there's no time for that. Instead you relax, empty your mind, and let your eyes, reflexes, and fingers play and learn. There are no patterns to memorize or level layouts to rehearse; each sub-minute ""game"" unfurls randomly enough to prevent rote training. There are no powerups to acquire or new abilities to unlock; the only thing leveling up is you, the player. You fail, and fail, and yet your best times slowly creep higher as the substrate of your brain manufactures aSuper Hexagonlayer. Then perhaps you take a break, and the pulsing soundtrack and whirling geometric shapes linger in your skull, reinforcing your neural net for the next session. It's as much meditative practice as game.Don't expect to beat this one without many hours of practice on what is, to all accounts, an otherwise useless skill set. But for a few dollars, you can partake of a pastime with no analogue, a memorable artifact with the soul ofCentipede,Tempest, and all the other pure video games of our era."
